{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":129,"record_hash":"sha256:d87eaf98ee33979aca3d046da9feb49c512860d1ca439f2a0fbecf596c508689","timestamp":"2026-05-20T00:58:28.465Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: fdfdd3\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3279\nOutput:\n   261\tworktree can have multiple unrelated applied branches at once.\n   262\t\n   263\t### Signal 2: Previous Worktree Files Becoming Committed Files\n   264\t\n   265\tFor each non-first turn, compare the previous turn's uncommitted worktree files\n   266\tagainst the current turn's observed branch commits.\n   267\t\n   268\tQuestion:\n   269\t\n   270\t> Are any files from the previous turn's uncommitted worktree file list present\n   271\t> in any commit file list in any branch observed in the current turn?\n   272\t\n   273\tIf yes, that is a strong association signal. It suggests work that was\n   274\tuncommitted at the end of one agent interaction later landed in a commit visible\n   275\tat the next capture.\n   276\t\n   277\tIf the matched commit has a change id, the association can point at that change\n   278\tid. If the matched branch has a review identifier, the association can point at\n   279\tthat review unit or pull request.\n   280\t\n   281\tIf a commit happens after one stop hook and before the next agent interaction,\n   282\tthe commit belongs to the interval between two observed turns. Do not create a\n   283\tfake empty turn to represent it. Store the real turn snapshots and derive the\n   284\tinterval evidence later.\n   285\t\n   286\t### Signal 3: Explicit Relationships\n   287\t\n   288\tExplicit attachment still matters. If the user, CLI, commit UI, or review UI\n   289\tconfirms that a session or turn is related to a target, that relationship is\n   290\tstronger than inference.\n   291\t\n   292\tThe likely product path is:\n   293\t\n   294\t```text\n   295\tturn evidence ranks suggestions\n   296\tuser/API confirmation writes durable relationships\n   297\t```\n   298\t\n   299\t## Session-Level Versus Turn-Level Association\n   300\t\n   301\tOpen question: how should association data from turns relate to session-level\n   302\trelationships?\n   303\t\n   304\tPossible answers:\n   305\t\n   306\t- **No propagation:** keep turn-level evidence only, and\n[TRUNCATED]\nd plain Git mode?\n   482\t- Checked-out references: is this a real field, or just a derived projection of\n   483\t  stacks and branches?\n   484\t- Association strength: which signals are strong enough to preselect a\n   485\t  suggested relationship?\n   486\t- Confirmation UX: should commit UI, PR/review publishing, or both ask the user\n   487\t  to confirm suggested sessions or turns?\n   488\t- Relationship scope: what is the smallest metadata shape that supports a\n   489\t  target-to-session relationship plus optional turn scope?\n   490\t- Propagation: if turn evidence points at a change id, should branch and PR\n   491\t  views derive that relationship, or should confirmed metadata be copied upward?\n   492\t- Plain Git operations: how should commits, rebases, and squashes outside\n   493\t  GitButler affect turn-derived evidence?\n   494\t\n   495\t## Implementation Implications\n   496\t\n   497\tThe current implementation in `crates/but-agentlog` already has the pieces that\n   498\tmake a turn layer plausible:\n   499\t\n   500\t- `record_transcript` snapshots a transcript file\n   501\t- `TranscriptBatch::parse` returns parsed records plus session/source metadata\n   502\t- `write_transcript_batch` filters records through `:record-hashes`\n   503\t- transcript records already carry `source_key`, `record_index`, and\n   504\t  `record_hash`\n   505\t\n   506\tThe missing piece is that `write_transcript_batch` throws away the batch\n   507\tboundary after appending records. A turn writer would need to receive the set of\n   508\tnewly accepted records and write a corresponding turn object.\n   509\t\n   510\tOne possible storage shape:\n   511\t\n   512\t```text\n   513\tgitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\n   514\tgitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n   515\t```\n   516\t\n   517\tWhere `TurnSummary` is cheap to scan and `TurnDetail` contains record\n   518\tmembership plus the environment snapshot. The exact GitMeta representation needs\n   519\tchecking against list/set/record ergonomics.\n   520\t\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T00:58:28.465Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}